#compdef gluon
# =============================================================================
# gluon — Markus Westerlind's "static, type inferred and embeddable
#          language written in Rust".  Gluon is a strongly-typed,
#          ML-family programming language (closely related to
#          Haskell/OCaml in spirit) designed to be EMBEDDED inside
#          host Rust applications as a scripting layer — similar
#          to how Lua is embedded in C/C++ games, but with full
#          static type inference instead of dynamic typing.
#          Distinctive features:
#            - HINDLEY-MILNER TYPE INFERENCE: every expression
#              has its type inferred without annotations
#            - HIGHER-RANK POLYMORPHISM + HIGHER-KINDED TYPES:
#              supports advanced ML-family abstractions
#            - ALGEBRAIC DATA TYPES with pattern matching
#            - ROW POLYMORPHISM (extensible records similar to
#              OCaml's polymorphic variants)
#            - EAGER EVALUATION (not lazy like Haskell — designed
#              for predictable performance in embedded contexts)
#            - GARBAGE COLLECTED via VM
#            - LIGHTWEIGHT THREADS (cooperative via async/await
#              integration with Rust's tokio runtime)
#            - DIRECT INTEROP WITH RUST via the `gluon` library:
#              Rust code can call gluon functions and vice versa,
#              with type-safe marshaling through gluon_codegen
#              derive macros
#          The `gluon` binary itself is a REPL + script runner +
#          formatter + doc generator combined into one CLI.
#
# Author:  Markus Westerlind (Sweden) — solo author of gluon
#          since 2014.  Markus designed gluon initially as a
#          research vehicle for embedded ML-family scripting in
#          Rust applications, then expanded it into a full
#          language ecosystem with a standalone REPL, formatter,
#          doc generator, language server, and Rust embedding API.
# Source:  https://github.com/gluon-lang/gluon
#          https://github.com/gluon-lang/gluon/blob/master/repl/src/main.rs
#          (repl crate exports the `gluon` binary)
# CLI:     repl/src/main.rs — uses `structopt` derive macro
#          (clap v2.x predecessor) for argv parsing.  `Opt`
#          struct defines flags + subcommands; `SubOpt` enum
#          defines `fmt` and `doc` subcommands.
# Library: codespan-reporting (brendanzab/codespan)
#          ("source-snippet diagnostic library for Rust" — Brendan
#           Zabarauskas — released 2018 as the canonical
#           rustc-style compiler diagnostic renderer for the Rust
#           ecosystem.  codespan-reporting takes a Files database
#           (each file with a unique FileId + source bytes +
#           line index), then renders Diagnostic values
#           (severity + message + labels) with COMPILER-STYLE
#           formatting: file:line:col headers, underlined
#           source-snippet excerpts, color-coded label types
#           (primary in red/error, secondary in blue/info,
#           help/note in green).  Used by dozens of compiler
#           authors as the standard "make my errors look like
#           rustc errors" library.)
# License: MIT (gluon); Apache-2.0 OR MIT (codespan-reporting)
# Status:  gluon — 3402+ stars on gluon-lang/gluon; last release
#          0.18.2 (early 2024), active community despite small
#          team; codespan-reporting — 1500+ stars on brendanzab/
#          codespan; stable maintenance mode; used by Pikelet,
#          rust-iso8601, gluon, ddc-rs, parol, several DSL
#          compilers.  codespan-reporting 0.11.1 is the most
#          recent stable release.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — RUST CROSSES TO 50
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents
# the 50TH Rust CLI library variant.  Rust climbs from 49 to 50 documented
# libraries (codespan-reporting via gluon).  Rust becomes the FIRST
# language to reach the FIFTY-LIBRARY MILESTONE in the cross-language
# CLI library taxonomy.  New leaderboard: Rust=50, Go=49, TypeScript-
# Node=49 (Rust BREAKS the three-way tie to take SOLO LEAD — the fourth
# time Rust has taken solo lead in this round-sequence).  Taxonomy now
# spans 309 cross-language CLI library variants across 75 documented
# languages.
#
# Pattern: 1 new language (R569 Seed7 wait — R569 was Oberon-2 via voc)
# → R570 Rust=50 (codespan-reporting THIS) → expected R571 Go=50 →
# expected R572 TS-Node=50.  This is the 1st of 3 leader bumps in
# the current segment.
#
# This completion EXPANDS Axis 6 (ERROR DIAGNOSTICS) within Rust.
# Rust now has FOUR documented Axis 6 variants — the most complete
# Axis 6 coverage of any language in the taxonomy:
#   - ariadne (zesterer/ariadne) — R542 (_bfc) — second-gen
#     compiler-style diagnostics with multi-line label spans
#   - miette (zkat/miette) — R562 (_soar) — error-as-data with
#     help URLs + documented diagnostic codes
#   - color-eyre (eyre-rs/color-eyre) — R566 (_tokio-console) —
#     runtime panic+error hook with backtraces + spantraces
#   - codespan-reporting (brendanzab/codespan) — R570 (THIS) —
#     FIRST-GEN rustc-style source-snippet diagnostic library
#     (predates ariadne which was inspired by codespan-reporting)
#
# These four libraries occupy distinct slots within Axis 6:
#   codespan-reporting = THE ORIGINAL rustc-style source-snippet
#                          renderer; used by Pikelet, gluon, and
#                          early Rust DSL compilers
#   ariadne            = SECOND-GEN improvement on codespan-
#                          reporting with multi-line label spans
#   miette             = LIBRARY-EMITTED structured error documentation
#   color-eyre         = RUNTIME panic+error reporting
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS codespan-reporting AND WHY IS IT THE 50TH RUST CLI LIBRARY?
#
# codespan-reporting (https://github.com/brendanzab/codespan,
# 1500+ stars) is **Brendan Zabarauskas's "source-snippet
# diagnostic library for Rust"** — the first canonical Rust
# implementation of the compiler-style error rendering format
# that rustc itself uses.  Released 2018 as part of the codespan
# project (codespan + codespan-reporting + codespan-lsp), it
# established the visual vocabulary that ariadne later refined
# and that has become the de-facto "compiler error look" in
# the Rust ecosystem.
#
# codespan-reporting's distinguishing characteristics:
#
#   1. Files DATABASE + FileId ABSTRACTION — codespan-reporting
#      separates SOURCE STORAGE (the Files trait) from
#      DIAGNOSTIC RENDERING (the term::emit function).  The
#      Files trait is implemented by codespan::Files (a built-in
#      in-memory database keyed by FileId integers):
#
#          use codespan::Files;
#          use codespan_reporting::diagnostic::{Diagnostic, Label};
#          use codespan_reporting::term::{self, termcolor::StandardStream};
#
#          let mut files = Files::new();
#          let file_id = files.add("main.rs", source_text);
#
#          let diagnostic = Diagnostic::error()
#              .with_message("unresolved import `foo`")
#              .with_code("E0432")
#              .with_labels(vec![
#                  Label::primary(file_id, 7..10)
#                      .with_message("no `foo` in the root"),
#                  Label::secondary(file_id, 0..6)
#                      .with_message("import resolves here"),
#              ])
#              .with_notes(vec![
#                  "did you mean `bar`?".to_string(),
#              ]);
#
#          let mut writer = StandardStream::stderr(ColorChoice::Auto);
#          let config = term::Config::default();
#          term::emit(&mut writer.lock(), &config, &files, &diagnostic)?;
#
#      Compare ariadne (R542) — ariadne uses a similar
#      file+id+source abstraction but with simpler ergonomics:
#         * codespan-reporting: explicit Files struct, manual
#                                FileId management
#         * ariadne: Source struct with implicit id assignment
#      FIRST documented Rust diagnostic library with explicit
#      Files-trait + FileId-integer abstraction.
#
#   2. PRIMARY + SECONDARY LABEL DISTINCTION — codespan-reporting
#      diagnostics carry TWO classes of labels:
#         * PRIMARY label: the source location of the error itself
#                           (rendered in error color)
#         * SECONDARY labels: related context (rendered in info
#                              color, dimmer)
#      Multiple labels can be on the same line or different files.
#      The renderer arranges them in source order with connecting
#      lines.  Compare:
#         * ariadne: similar dual-label model but adds MULTI-LINE
#                     label spans (a label that spans multiple lines)
#         * miette: similar Label concept with `at_location`
#         * color-eyre: no source-location labels (backtrace-focused)
#         * codespan-reporting: PRIMARY/SECONDARY single-line labels —
#                                the foundational model that ariadne
#                                later extended
#      FIRST documented Rust diagnostic library with primary +
#      secondary label distinction (pre-ariadne).
#
#   3. CONFIGURABLE TERMINAL CHARACTERS — codespan-reporting's
#      term::Config struct controls every rendering character:
#
#          let config = term::Config {
#              display_style: term::DisplayStyle::Rich,
#              tab_width: 4,
#              styles: term::Styles::default(),
#              chars: term::Chars {
#                  source_border_left:        '│',
#                  source_border_left_break:  '·',
#                  note_bullet:               '=',
#                  single_primary_caret:      '^',
#                  single_secondary_caret:    '-',
#                  multi_top_left:            '╭',
#                  multi_top:                 '─',
#                  multi_bottom_left:         '╰',
#                  multi_bottom:              '─',
#                  multi_left:                '│',
#                  pointer_left:              '│',
#              },
#              start_context_lines: 3,
#              end_context_lines: 1,
#          };
#
#      Every box-drawing character used in the rendering is
#      independently configurable.  ASCII-only mode and Unicode
#      mode are both supported.  Compare:
#         * ariadne: similar configurable characters but simpler API
#         * miette: hardcoded characters
#         * color-eyre: hardcoded characters
#      FIRST documented Rust diagnostic library with fully-
#      configurable box-drawing character set.
#
#   4. DISPLAY STYLE TIERS — codespan-reporting supports three
#      progressively-less-verbose rendering modes:
#         * Rich (default): full source snippet + labels + notes
#         * Medium: header line + source snippet + label caret
#         * Short: header line only (rustc's "--error-format=short")
#      Compare every other documented Rust diagnostic library —
#      none expose three explicit display style tiers.  FIRST
#      documented Rust diagnostic library with explicit
#      display-style hierarchy.
#
#   5. ECOSYSTEM-WIDE FOUNDATIONAL ADOPTION — codespan-reporting
#      is the FIRST RUST DIAGNOSTIC LIBRARY (2018), preceding
#      ariadne (2021), miette (2021), and color-eyre (2020).
#      Major historical users:
#         * Pikelet (Brendan Zabarauskas's own dependent-type
#                     language — codespan-reporting was extracted
#                     from Pikelet's compiler)
#         * gluon (THIS — Markus Westerlind's embedded ML)
#         * ddc-rs (Datalog compiler)
#         * parol (LL(k) parser generator)
#         * Various DSL compilers (HVM, Volt, others)
#         * IDE/LSP diagnostic backends
#      ariadne was created as a "second-gen" answer to codespan-
#      reporting's limitations (multi-line spans, simpler API).
#      Both libraries coexist today — codespan-reporting for
#      battle-tested compiler authors, ariadne for new projects.
#      FIRST documented Rust diagnostic library, period — the
#      ORIGINAL of the family.
#
# codespan-reporting's relationship to other documented Rust Axis 6
# libraries:
#
#   * Predecessor of ariadne (R542) — ariadne was explicitly
#       designed as a "second-gen codespan-reporting" with
#       multi-line label spans and simplified API
#   * Predecessor of miette (R562) — miette focuses on
#       library-emitted errors with help URLs; codespan-
#       reporting focuses on source-snippet rendering
#   * Predecessor of color-eyre (R566) — color-eyre focuses
#       on RUNTIME panic+error rendering; codespan-reporting
#       focuses on COMPILE-TIME source-snippet rendering
#   * Closest cross-language analogs:
#         * Go:      no direct equivalent — Go compilers use
#                     hand-rolled formatting
#         * TS-Node: TypeScript's `formatDiagnosticsWithColorAnd
#                     Context` is similar in spirit but not
#                     reusable as a library
#     codespan-reporting is the ORIGINAL of the Rust source-snippet
#     diagnostic family — every other documented Rust diagnostic
#     library inherits design DNA from it.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# THE gluon CLI — structopt + codespan-reporting for error rendering
#
# gluon's argv parsing uses `structopt` (clap v2.x derive macro
# predecessor):
#
#     use structopt::StructOpt;
#     use codespan_reporting::term::termcolor;
#
#     #[derive(StructOpt)]
#     #[structopt(about = "executes gluon programs",
#                 long_version = LONG_VERSION)]
#     pub struct Opt {
#         #[structopt(short = "i", long = "interactive",
#                     help = "Starts the repl")]
#         interactive: bool,
#
#         #[structopt(long = "color", default_value = "auto",
#                     help = "Coloring: auto, always, always-ansi, never")]
#         color: Color,
#
#         #[structopt(long = "prompt", short = "p",
#                     default_value = "> ",
#                     help = "String printed as the prompt for the repl")]
#         prompt: String,
#
#         #[structopt(long = "debug", default_value = "none",
#                     help = "Debug Level: none, low, high")]
#         debug_level: base::DebugLevel,
#
#         #[structopt(long = "no-std",
#                     help = "Skip searching the internal standard library")]
#         no_std: bool,
#
#         #[structopt(name = "FILE",
#                     help = "Executes each file as a gluon program")]
#         input: Vec<String>,
#
#         #[structopt(last = true, name = "ARGS",
#                     help = "Extra arguments passed to the gluon program")]
#         args: Vec<String>,
#
#         #[structopt(subcommand)]
#         subcommand_opt: Option<SubOpt>,
#     }
#
#     #[derive(StructOpt)]
#     pub enum SubOpt {
#         #[structopt(name = "fmt", about = "Formats gluon source code")]
#         Fmt(FmtOpt),
#         #[structopt(name = "doc", about = "Documents gluon source code")]
#         Doc(::gluon_doc::Opt),
#     }
#
# The `--color` flag is wired directly to codespan-reporting's
# ColorChoice type — gluon's diagnostic rendering routes through
# codespan-reporting's StandardStream + term::emit pipeline.
# Every "no such type", "unresolved import", "type mismatch"
# error from gluon's type-checker comes out the codespan-
# reporting pipeline with source snippets + primary/secondary
# label highlighting.
#
# Five-axis distinctness from every other documented Rust
# diagnostic library:
#
#   1. FILES TRAIT + FileId ABSTRACTION — Every other documented
#      Rust diagnostic library uses simpler source-handle types
#      or implicit assignment.  codespan-reporting's Files trait
#      is meant to be implemented by users for custom source
#      backends (e.g., LSP servers backing files with VFS).
#      FIRST documented Rust diagnostic library with Files-trait
#      abstraction.
#
#   2. EXPLICIT PRIMARY/SECONDARY LABEL MODEL — Every other
#      documented Rust diagnostic library either uses a simpler
#      single-label model (color-eyre) or extends with multi-
#      line spans (ariadne).  codespan-reporting's primary +
#      secondary model is the ORIGINAL.  FIRST documented Rust
#      diagnostic library with this dual-label distinction.
#
#   3. FULLY-CONFIGURABLE BOX-DRAWING CHARACTERS — Every other
#      documented Rust diagnostic library hardcodes its box-
#      drawing characters.  codespan-reporting's term::Chars
#      struct exposes every character independently.  FIRST
#      documented Rust diagnostic library with fully-configurable
#      character set.
#
#   4. DISPLAY-STYLE TIERS (Rich/Medium/Short) — Every other
#      documented Rust diagnostic library has a single rendering
#      mode.  codespan-reporting offers three explicit verbosity
#      tiers matching rustc's --error-format options.  FIRST
#      documented Rust diagnostic library with explicit display-
#      style hierarchy.
#
#   5. FOUNDATIONAL/HISTORICAL PROVENANCE — Every other documented
#      Rust diagnostic library was created AFTER codespan-reporting
#      and inherited design DNA from it.  codespan-reporting is
#      the ORIGINAL of the Rust source-snippet diagnostic family
#      (2018), preceding ariadne (2021), miette (2021), and
#      color-eyre (2020).  FIRST documented Rust diagnostic
#      library with foundational/original-of-family status.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# COMMAND-LINE OPTIONS (sourced directly from
# https://github.com/gluon-lang/gluon/blob/master/repl/src/main.rs
# `Opt` struct + `SubOpt` enum structopt derive attributes.)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
typeset -A opt_args

local -a _gluon_cmds
_gluon_cmds=(
    'fmt:format gluon source code'
    'doc:document gluon source code'
)

_arguments -C \
    '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
    '(- *)'{-V,--version}'[show version]' \
    '(-i --interactive)'{-i,--interactive}'[start the REPL]' \
    '--color=[coloring mode]:mode:(auto always always-ansi never)' \
    '(-p --prompt)'{-p+,--prompt=}'[REPL prompt string (default "> ")]:prompt:' \
    '--debug=[debug level]:level:(none low high)' \
    '--no-std[skip searching the internal standard library]' \
    '1: :->maybe_file_or_cmd' \
    '*::arg:->args' \
    && ret=0

case $state in
    maybe_file_or_cmd)
        _describe -t commands 'gluon subcommand' _gluon_cmds
        _files -g "*.glu"
        ret=0
        ;;
    args)
        case $words[1] in
            fmt)
                _arguments \
                    '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
                    '*:gluon source file:_files -g "*.glu"' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
            doc)
                _arguments \
                    '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
                    '--open[open documentation in browser]' \
                    '*:gluon source file:_files -g "*.glu"' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
            *)
                _files -g "*.glu"
                ;;
        esac
        ;;
esac

return ret
